urological examination reveals reduced sensation over the lateral aspect of the left foot and weakness in dorsiflexion of the left foot.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the main branches of the sacral plexus is a mixed nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior gluteal nerve","Axillary nerve","Sciatic nerve","Posterior femoral cutaneous nerve","Inferior gluteal nerve"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is the largest branch of the sacral plexus and is a mixed nerve, meaning it contains both motor and sensory fibers. It arises from nerve roots \u003Cstrong\u003EL4-S3\u003C/strong\u003E and provides motor innervation to muscles in the posterior thigh and all muscles below the knee, as well as sensory innervation to the skin of the leg and foot (via its terminal branches: the tibial nerve and common fibular nerve).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior gluteal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a motor nerve that innervates the gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, and tensor fasciae latae muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is not a branch of the sacral plexus; it is a branch of the brachial plexus and innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles, as well as providing sensory innervation to the skin over the deltoid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior femoral cutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a sensory nerve that provides sensation to the skin of the posterior thigh and perineum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior gluteal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a motor nerve that innervates the gluteus maximus muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sciatic nerve is the largest and longest nerve in the human body, originating from the sacral plexus.","The sciatic nerve is a mixed nerve, containing both motor and sensory fibers.","The sciatic nerve innervates the posterior thigh muscles and all muscles of the leg and foot."],"references":["Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Matejc\u00edk V. Anatomical variations of lumbosacral plexus. Surg Radiol Anat. 2010 Apr;32(4):409-14. doi: 10.1007/s00276-009-0546-3. Epub 2009 Aug 21. PMID: 19696958."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T21:06:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T21:07:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9996"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70167"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":""